{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"591eea70-8ec7-42f2-909d-1e18dc34a7c2","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform tool for .NET performance analysis.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper analysis, ETW events, GC details |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) — check if CPU is in GC, JIT, or user code first |\n| **`dotnet-dump`** | If you suspect a tight loop — grab a dump and inspect thread stacks |\n\n### Recommended triage order:\n1. **`dotnet-counters`** first — quick sanity check (GC % time, threadpool queue length, etc.)\n2. **`dotnet-trace`** with `cpu-sampling` — identifies hot methods\n3. **PerfView** if you need kernel-level ETW data (e.g., context switching, I/O)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d6590a3c-6e75-4f16-8fed-404efb341004","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":396},"id":"941ed08a-71aa-4c29-9c27-85ca6ff1196e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:52:18.478Z","parentId":"741d7a0e-9e81-4508-bf74-6c6c61ee4257"}
